docs.abstract: Philip Dray’s book “A Lynching at Port Jervis” unearths the history of an 1892 murder of a Black man at the hands of a white mob.
docs.snippet: Philip Dray’s book “A Lynching at Port Jervis” unearths the history of an 1892 murder of a Black man at the hands of a white mob.
docs.lead_paragraph: On June 2, 1892, a white mob seized a Black man and hanged him from the high branch of an old maple tree in Port Jervis, N.Y. Several days later, a jury took all of an hour to deliver its verdict on what had happened: “Robert Lewis came to his death in the village of Port Jervis on June 2nd by being hanged by his neck by a person or persons unknown.”

headline.main: When Jim Crow Violence Came to a Small New York Village
headline.print_headline: Jim Crow Violence Close to Home

docs.abstract: Daily, biweekly and weekly shows deliver kids the news at their level, and help contextualize the world around them.
docs.snippet: Daily, biweekly and weekly shows deliver kids the news at their level, and help contextualize the world around them.
docs.lead_paragraph: What do children make of the day’s headlines? The endless deluge of news is staggering and tough to get a handle on, even for grown-ups. And with disinformation packaged as journalism rampant on social media, there is an urgent need to help kids tell the difference between truth and propaganda. These news podcasts are perfect for young people seeking a better understanding of what the adults are fussing about and for parents who want to help their children learn how to engage critically with the world around them.

headline.main: 4 Current Affairs Podcasts for Curious Children

docs.abstract: Adam Hollingsworth, known in Chicago as the Dreadhead Cowboy, is trying to spread a positive message on horseback. But a popular video of him has been widely misinterpreted.
docs.snippet: Adam Hollingsworth, known in Chicago as the Dreadhead Cowboy, is trying to spread a positive message on horseback. But a popular video of him has been widely misinterpreted.
docs.lead_paragraph: In late May, as protests against police brutality began to seize American cities, videos of a Black man on horseback wearing a bulletproof vest spread widely on social media. In many of the posts, users suggested that he had stolen a policeman’s horse.

headline.main: ‘You Can’t Just Get Up and Steal a Police Horse’

docs.abstract: The Working Families Party wants to represent the resistance.
docs.snippet: The Working Families Party wants to represent the resistance.
docs.lead_paragraph: During the 20 years that he has led the social democratic Working Families Party, Dan Cantor has waited for the left to get serious about building power through local politics. “People, sophisticated people, barely know who their state senator is,” he told me. A significant portion of nonmilitary spending in America is done at the state and local levels, he pointed out, “so it’s not like these are trivial offices. This is where people live.”

docs.snippet: Stacey Abrams is concerned about Black male turnout in her race for governor in Georgia. She’s not the only Democrat who should be worried.
docs.lead_paragraph: Last month in a videotaped appearance for a “Pod Save America” live show, Stacey Abrams, a celebrated Democratic activist and the Democratic nominee for governor of Georgia, said that Black men have the power to determine the election in that state.

docs.abstract: At the Brooklyn Museum, a tribute to fashion’s showman who built temples out of curves and proved clothing had metamorphic properties.
docs.snippet: At the Brooklyn Museum, a tribute to fashion’s showman who built temples out of curves and proved clothing had metamorphic properties.
docs.lead_paragraph: Manfred Thierry Mugler, the boundary-pushing French couturier whose glamazons and fembots helped define fashion in the 1980s and ’90s and who died earlier this year, famously hated retrospectives. “In the museum world, everyone knew he was against the idea,” said Thierry-Maxime Loriot, the curator at the Montreal Museum of Fine Arts, the institution that finally convinced Mugler to reconsider.

headline.main: Thierry Mugler: Nothing Is Ever Too Extreme
